":"1480–1540","about 1480":"okolo 1480","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"about 1480–1540":"omkring 1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Afdød","1500–Female":"1500–Afdød","1480–1540":"1480–1540","about 1480":"omkring 1480","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1480–1540":"circa 1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Overleden","1500–Female":"1500–Overleden","1480–1540":"1480–1540","about 1480":"circa 1480","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1480–1540":"about 1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","1500–Female":"1500–Deceased","1480–1540":"1480–1540","about 1480":"about 1480","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"McMinn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Méinn</b> ‘son of <i>Méinn</i>’, a Gaelic interpretation of   Menzies   as a relationship surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Menzies","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Manners  , in which the <i>z</i> was originally the Middle English letter <i>ʒ</i> (yogh), representing a sound similar to modern English <i>y</i>. The surname is pronounced <i>Meenyus</i> or <i>Minyas</i> in Scotland. The name was brought to Scotland in the 12th or 13th century by a family of Norman knights. It appears that the name was re-interpreted in Gaelic as containing a personal name, and for variants ending <i>-s</i> there is a possibility of confusion with   McManus  . See also   McMinn  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"George McMinn was born about 1480, in England. He married Mary Shaw in 1500, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1540, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"about 1480–1540":"umbes 1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1480–1540":"1480–1540","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1480–1540":"noin 1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1480–1540":"1480–1540","about 1480":"noin 1480","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1480–1540":"environ 1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Décédée","1500–Female":"1500–Décédée","1480–1540":"1480–1540","about 1480":"environ 1480","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"George McMinn est né environ 1480, à Angleterre. Il a épousé Mary Shaw en 1500, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1540, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 61 ans."},"de":{"about 1480–1540":"um 1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Verstorben","1500–Female":"1500